data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code in EF Core 10:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your expression-tree building code **won't compile**. The new overload accepts `Func<...>` instead of `Expression<Func<...>>`, so you can use simple imperative code:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

Delete all the `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery.

---

## 2. Complex type column names — two sub-changes

### a) Same-named properties across sibling complex types are now **uniquified**

Previously `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` silently shared one column. Now EF appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep the old mapping, pin the names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

### b) Nested complex types now use the **full path** in column names

`Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve old names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Action**: generate a new migration after upgrading and inspect column renames. Either accept the new names or pin with `HasColumnName`.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) gained a trailing `string logCommandText` parameter that carries the (potentially redacted) SQL for logging:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add the parameter to **all** implemented methods from this interface or you'll get compile errors.
